Visit our bio link to see more from @leewayhome.

node.text: Eileen Mockus, CEO of sustainable homeware company @Coyuchi, talks with @archdigestpro editor @katy_magic about how to make your home more sustainable by making a few simple design choices.

node.title: In Conversation: Eileen Mockus, CEO of @coyuchi

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 23, 2021. May be an image of furniture and indoor.

node.text:
Because this three-story house in Montana was still being built when designer Roger Higgins (@rhigginsinteriors) and his team arrived on site, they had the opportunity to customize paint colors, carpeting, and light fixtures right from the get-go. They chose neutral carpeting and wide-plank wood floors in order to provide a solid aesthetic foundation, which was later dressed up with antique area rugs. 

Tour the mountainside home at our bio link. Photo by @haris.kenjar; design by @rhigginsinteriors; words by @ericrallen.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 23, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
Musician @mileycyrus's studio is “definitely a vibe.” The trippy ceiling was painted by surface designer @brianrobles, and it has multiple inspirations. Says mom and designer @tishcyrus, “It started with the throw pillows. I had found those at Barneys before Barneys went out of business. I just knew at some point, Miley’s going to need these.” When Tish and design Mat Sanders (@thematfinish) suggested they play off the colorful waves in the pillows’ psychedelic designs for the mural, Tish says, “Miley agreed, then added, ‘Yeah, but it should also feel like vaginas.’ I was like, Okay!”

Tour the whole home at our bio link. Photo by @jennapeffley; design by @tishcyrus and @thematfinish; words by @arielfoxman.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 23, 2021. May be an image of living room and hearth.

node.text:
The layout of this family home on Lake Champlain may be complex, but the detailing and materials are firmly rooted in local traditions. “We did a lot of research,” says architect Gil Schafer (@gpschafer), “especially at the nearby @shelburnemuseum and its collection of historic buildings. Some of my friends questioned the crazy-quilt stone masonry on the façade, but, in fact, it is exactly the same as on one of the houses there. We looked to the big, old summer houses of the later-19th and early-20th centuries for inspiration. That’s why the living room and entry are paneled with vertical boards, why we decided on knotty pine for the library.”

Tour the home at our bio link. Photo by @ericpiasecki; architecture by @gpschafer; design by Patti Smith; styling by @helencrowther; words by @michaelboodro.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 22, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
“Instead of going to Europe or someplace else out of the country, everyone wants to go to a national park,” says Colleen O’Keefe, a luxury travel adviser and national parks specialist who is the founder of @theglobalconcierge. “My phones have been ringing nonstop with clients who are rushing to book their trips before summer starts.”

See some of the incredible hotels near national parks (like @amangiri) at our bio link. Photo by @joefletcherphoto; words by @shivanivora78.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 22, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
Model @taylor_hill left her historic Nashville home's upstairs guest bathroom as found, having fallen for the bold striped wallpaper and deep copper tub. “I’m obsessed with this tub,” she says. “Copper is a heat-conducting metal, so when the hot water is in it, it just stays warm, and you don’t have to continually add hot water. In the winter or the fall, I use it almost every day.”

See more from her home at our bio link. Photo by @alyssarosenheck; styled by @alyssarosenheck; words by @libbycallaway1970.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 21, 2021. May be an image of furniture and bedroom.

node.text:
“I want people to feel good in the house,” says Los Angeles developer and former fashion designer @philippenaouri about his home: an Edward Fickett midcentury home in Malibu he saved from being torn down. “The house is made so that you can relax and enjoy your life. It’s not made to be a museum.”

Explore the retro home at our bio link. Photo by @douglasfriedman; design by @philippenaouri; words by @sheilaym.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 21, 2021. May be an image of living room.

node.text:
@rushjenkins and @klausbaer remember the moment in @yellowstonenps when they decided to abandon the big city life in Manhattan. “We were driving a convertible and it was a gorgeous day in May with snow-capped mountains everywhere,” recalls Jenkins, the former director of design at @sotheby’s New York and a co-founder of @wrjdesign. “We turned to each other and were like, if we don't do this now, when are we going to do this? So we made it happen.”

Tour the Wyoming home they designed at our bio link. Photo by @ericpiasecki; design by @wrjdesign; architecture by @berlin_architects; words by @jenniferleeflowers.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 21, 2021. May be an image of furniture, sink and kitchen.

node.text:
“The [primary] bedroom feels like it’s floating in the clouds, and I absolutely love it,” says Vanessa Alexander (@alexanderdesignbuild), designer of @soulcycle cofounder @julierice_’s Montauk retreat. “Now the bedroom is this perfectly intimate size, a dreamy space that’s very ethereal, with linen drapes from de Le Cuona that the sun filters through.” Rice agrees, “the [primary] bedroom-bathroom situation is pretty epic. Vanessa tricked it out in the best way possible, so it feels like the most amazing, luxurious kind of hotel suite ever.” Plaster-wrapped, with a glass-ceiling double-rainfall shower, the bathroom is a particular area of envy for the rest of the family.

Explore the contemporary home at our bio link. @chrismottalini; architecture by @stevenharrisarchitects; renovation by @resolution4architecture; design by @alexanderdesignbuild; words by @katromeyn.

“I like things that have a sense of humor and playfulness, but I also like architectural rigor and old rattan, and I like combining all that with a Colombian carpet or Stilnovo sconces,” decorator Esteban Arboleda (@estebannyc) of @haynesrobertsinc says about his Shelter Island home. “The house accepts it all. You can bring in a lot of things from different eras.” It’s an ease, of course, that only comes with expertise. Notes husband @davidghaskell, very much in awe of his other half, “there is a lot of talent in being able to pull all that together in a way that is inviting and not chaotic.”

Tour the home at our bio link. Photo by @stephenkentjohnson; words by @samuelcochran.

Who says a children’s bedroom has to be boisterous and bright? In the case of this Manhattan skyscraper, the opposite is true. The Pierre Paulin chair is covered in Maharam fabric, and D. Porthault sheets appoint the mahogany bunk bed. “We didn’t want the spaces to feel as if there was too much going on,” designer Steven Volpe (@studiovolpe_sv) said to AD at the time. “The decorative effects are calculated for subtlety, not artificial drama. When you’re in the apartment, you sense the quality. It’s quiet, but you feel it.”

See some of the best-designed kids' rooms – and more design trend news from @archdigestpro – at our bio link. Photo by @stephenkentjohnson; styled by @michaelreynoldsnyc; design by @studiovolpe_sv; words by @madeleineluckel.

“When you go to the Champs-Élysées in Paris and you walk toward the Hermès or Louis Vuitton [store], the façade is very old and classical,” explains Shashi Reddy, the homeowner of this Atlanta home. “But after you enter, the space has this wonderful lighting, these very clean lines, and the antiquated feeling goes away. That’s what we were looking for in our home—we wanted the space to fit the neighborhood but to have interiors that matched our personalities.”

Tour the home at our bio link. Photo by @mali_azima; design by @joelkellydesign and @wyethrayinteriors; lighting design by @orsmandesign; words by @iamnickmafi.

It all started with a piano and a chance encounter in Paris. “The apartment has been in the family since the late 1970s,” the Beirut-born inhabitant explains of her abode, which is located not far from the Arc de Triomphe. “The previous owner had this piano and said, ‘If you want the apartment, you have to take the piano,’ since he didn’t want to move it out. It then became the starting point for everything [that followed].”

Tour this historic Parisian apartment at our bio link. Photo by @nicolas4matheus; design by @benoitdupuisarchitectes; words by @gaygassmann.
